        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-07-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-07-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="89"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d89">
                <head>89. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VC_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d89fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 18, Evening Reports
                        (State) 7/77. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote
                        “Cy, J” in the upper right corner.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-07-28">July 28, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here are items unrelated to Central Africa.]</p>
                <p>3. <hi rend="italic">Zaire’s Foreign Minister:</hi> In my meeting last night,
                    Zairian Foreign Affairs Commissioner <persName corresp="#p_NK_1"
                        >Nguza</persName> described President <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1"
                        >Mobutu</persName>’s proposed political, economic and military reforms. They
                    are clearly designed, as <persName corresp="#p_NK_1">Nguza</persName> frankly
                    stated, to meet external criticism of <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1"
                        >Mobutu</persName>’s government, particularly with respect to lack of
                    democratic practice and human rights abuses. If implemented, the reforms could
                    go a long way to meet the criticisms. On the economic side, <persName
                        corresp="#p_NK_1">Nguza</persName> acknowledged Zaire’s past mistakes and
                    corruption and reiterated several times that the reforms are intended to obtain
                    donor confidence and therefore greater external economic assistance.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d89fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote “He may be biased in
                        views” in the left margin.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NK_1">Nguza</persName> described the internal Angolan
                    situation as “very bad.” He said <persName corresp="#p_NAA_1">Neto</persName>’s
                    relations with the Soviets and the Cubans have become strained; <persName
                        corresp="#p_NAA_1">Neto</persName>’s party is split on racial and political
                    grounds; the former guerrillas are pitted against the ideologues; and <persName
                        corresp="#p_NAA_1">Neto</persName>’s opponents within the ruling <gloss
                        target="#t_MPLA_1">MPLA</gloss> were disposed to compromise with <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJ_1">Savimbi</persName>.</p>
                <p>I asked <persName corresp="#p_NK_1">Nguza</persName> for his views on the
                    situation in Chad. <persName corresp="#p_NK_1">Nguza</persName> called <persName
                        corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> this morning and at lunch today told
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRM_1">Dick Moose</persName> that <persName
                        corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName>
                    <pb facs="0296" n="264" xml:id="pg_264"/> opposes the Libyan activity in Chad
                    which he considers to be a violation of Organization of African Unity
                    principles. Zaire will strongly support publicly and diplomatically actions to
                    assist Chad but would prefer not to provide direct assistance.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here are items unrelated to Central Africa.]</p>
            </div>
